{
  "final_answer": "## Starship R&D as a Percentage of Three Denominators — FY2025\n\n### The Data\n\n| Metric | FY2025 ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| **Starship R&D expense** | $3,004 |\n| **Space segment revenue** | $4,086 |\n| **Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | $653 |\n| **Consolidated revenue** | $18,674 |\n\n### The Calculations\n\n| Denominator | Ratio | Calculation |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Space segment revenue** | **73.52%** | $3,004M ÷ $4,086M |\n| **Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **460.03%** | $3,004M ÷ $653M |\n| **Consolidated revenue** | **16.09%** | $3,004M ÷ $18,674M |\n\n---\n\n### Which Denominator Provides the Most Informative View of Development Burden?\n\n**Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA — at 460.03% — provides the most informative view.** Here is the reasoning for each denominator:\n\n---\n\n#### 1. Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA (460.03%) — **Most Informative**\n\nThe concept of \"development burden\" is fundamentally about how a program weighs on a business's capacity to generate returns and sustain itself. Segment Adjusted EBITDA is the closest proxy for the segment's operational earnings power available in the filing. The 460% figure makes three things starkly clear:\n\n- **Starship R&D alone consumes 4.6× the segment's entire adjusted operating profit.** The Space segment would have generated approximately $3,657 million in Segment Adjusted EBITDA absent Starship R&D ($653M + $3,004M), meaning the program is not merely large — it *overwhelms* segment-level profitability and pushes the segment deep into operating losses ($657M loss from operations in FY2025).\n\n- **The Space segment cannot self-fund Starship from its own current earnings.** The 460% ratio directly quantifies the dependency on either cross-segment subsidization (from Connectivity and AI) or external capital. This is the essence of \"burden\": the program consumes more resources than the segment itself produces.\n\n- **It isolates the economic trade-off.** Management explicitly states it is prioritizing \"execution speed, capacity expansion, and technological leadership over near‑term margin optimization.\" The EBITDA ratio quantifies exactly how much near-term margin is being surrendered.\n\n#### 2. Space Segment Revenue (73.52%) — **Useful but Incomplete**\n\nThis ratio shows that Starship R&D consumes nearly three-quarters of the Space segment's top line — a classic R&D-intensity metric. It is directionally informative but misses the *economic* dimension of burden: revenue pays for many things besides R&D (cost of revenue, SG&A, etc.). High revenue does not imply capacity to absorb high R&D if gross margins are thin. The revenue-based ratio tells you about R&D ambition relative to commercial scale, but not about financial sustainability.\n\n#### 3. Consolidated Revenue (16.09%) — **Least Informative, Potentially Misleading**\n\nConsolidated revenue includes $11,387 million from the Connectivity segment (Starlink) and $3,201 million from the AI segment (xAI). Starship R&D is a Space-segment activity with no direct operational nexus to those other segments. Using consolidated revenue:\n\n- Dilutes the apparent burden by a factor of ~4.6× compared to Space segment revenue.\n- Obscures the fact that the Space segment is economically underwater because of Starship.\n- Implies — incorrectly — that the development program is modest relative to the overall enterprise, when in reality it is the dominant driver of the Space segment's financial profile.\n\nThe 16.09% figure could mislead an analyst into thinking Starship R&D is easily absorbable, when in fact it requires substantial cross-segment support.\n\n---\n\n### Conclusion\n\n**Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA is the most informative denominator** because it directly answers the core question of burden: *How does this development program weigh on the segment's capacity to produce economic returns?* At 460%, the answer is unambiguous — Starship R&D does not merely reduce Space segment profitability; it consumes it many times over, creating a structural dependence on other segments or capital sources that is the very definition of a development burden. The filing corroborates this: management explicitly attributes both the year-over-year decline in Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA (from $1,154M in FY2024 to $653M in FY2025) and the segment's deepening operating losses \"primarily\" to accelerated Starship investment, and expects R&D to moderate only \"once Starship is commercialized.\"\n\n---\n\n```json\n{\n  \"sources\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\",\n      \"name\": \"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```",
